{"title_page": "King Philip Regional High School", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n|name = King Philip Regional High School\n|established = 1957\n|type = [[high school|Public]]\n|head_name = Principal\n|head = Lisa Mobley \n|image = King Philip Regional High School Logo.gif\n|address = 201 Franklin Street\n|city = [[Wrentham, Massachusetts|Wrentham]]\n|state = [[Massachusetts|MA]] 02093\n|country = [[United States|USA]]\n|campus = [[Suburban]]\n|enrollment = 1,300 (2017\u201318)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=2506510&ID=250651000940|title=King Philip Regional High|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=January 5, 2020}}</ref>\n|faculty = 81.72 (FTE)<ref name=NCES/>\n|ratio = 15.91<ref name=NCES/>\n|class =\nMid 20s to Mid 30s\n|SAT = 580 verbal<br />573 math<br />1153 total (2017-2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://profiles.doe.mass.edu/statereport/sat.aspx|title=2017-18 SAT Performance Statewide Report|work=mass.edu|date=September 20, 2018|access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref>\n|colors = Green & Gold {{color box|green}} {{color box|gold}}\n|mascot = Warrior\n|homepage = {{url|https://www.kingphilip.org/HighSchool}}\n}}\n'''King Philip Regional High School''' is a regional high school in [[Massachusetts]] drawing students from three towns: [[Wrentham, Massachusetts|Wrentham]], [[Norfolk, Massachusetts|Norfolk]], and [[Plainville, Massachusetts|Plainville]].  The school is located at 201 Franklin Street in [[Wrentham, Massachusetts|Wrentham]].\n\n== Marching Band ==\nThe King Philip Regional High School Marching Band, known as \"The Pride and the Passion\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wickedlocal.com/article/20091116/News/311169336|title=KP's Pride and Passion: Marching Band Wins National Title|last=McCarron|first=Heather|date=|website=Wicked Local|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> has traveled throughout New England and the United States for state, regional, and national competitions including [[Massachusetts Instrumental and Choral Conductors Association]] (MICCA) marching band festivals,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://kingphilipmusic.weebly.com/marching-band.html|title=Marching Band|last=|first=|date=|website=King Philip Music Association|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> [[New England Scholastic Band Association]] competitions,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nesba.org/events/11032019/2019-New-England-Marching-Band-Championships/#|title=NESBA: New England Scholastic Band Association|website=www.nesba.org|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> [[USBands]] national competitions, and [[Bands of America]] Grand National competitions.\n\nAwards and titles won by the King Philip Marching Band include:\n\n* 33 consecutive MICCA Finals Gold Medal awards (1986\u20142019)<ref name=\":0\" />{{better source|reason=self sourced|date=April 2020}}\n* USBands Group 2 Open Class National Champions (1995)<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://yea.org/usbands/scores|title=USBands Scores|last=|first=|date=|website=yea.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n* USBands Group 3 Open Class National Champions (1998, 1999, 2013, 2015, 2016)<ref name=\":1\" />\n* USBands Group 4 Open Class National Champions (2009, 2012)<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Notable alumni and faculty==\n*[[Lofa Tatupu]] (2001), NFL linebacker<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/players/lofatatupu/profile?id=TAT743820|title=Lofa Tatupu|work=NFL.com|accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Jeff Plympton]], Former Red Sox Pitcher<ref>{{cite web|title=Jeff Plympton - The Baseball Cube|url=http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/P/jeff-plympton.shtml|work=The Baseball Cube |accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Jake Layman]], NBA player (Minnesota Timberwolves)\n*[[Joe Johnson (baseball)|Joe Johnson]], Former MLB Pitcher.<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Johnson Stats|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/j/johnsjo05.shtml|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Jeremy Udden]], musician.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesunchronicle.com/news/kp-grad-jeremy-udden-promotes-hometown-in-plainville-project/article_2adfb967-a2c4-5848-9264-fe9a6602be41.html|title=KP grad Jeremy Udden promotes hometown in 'Plainville' project|work=[[The Sun Chronicle]]|accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Liam Kyle Sullivan]], YouTuber{{citation needed|reason=linked article does not confirm attendance|date=January 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.kingphilip.org/HighSchool}}\n* {{Official|https://www.kingphilip.org/|district website}}\n\n{{Massachusetts Public High Schools}}\n\n{{coord|42|04|22.61|N|71|19|56.45|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Public high schools in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Schools in Norfolk County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Hockomock League]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n|name = King Philip Regional High School\n|established = 1957\n|type = [[high school|Public]]\n|head_name = Principal\n|head = Lisa Mobley \n|image = King Philip Regional High School Logo.gif\n|address = 201 Franklin Street\n|city = [[Wrentham, Massachusetts|Wrentham]]\n|state = [[Massachusetts|MA]] 02093\n|country = [[United States|USA]]\n|campus = [[Suburban]]\n|enrollment = 1,300 (2017\u201318)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=2506510&ID=250651000940|title=King Philip Regional High|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=January 5, 2020}}</ref>\n|faculty = 81.72 (FTE)<ref name=NCES/>\n|ratio = 15.91<ref name=NCES/>\n|class =\nMid 20s to Mid 30s\n|SAT = 580 verbal<br />573 math<br />1153 total (2017-2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://profiles.doe.mass.edu/statereport/sat.aspx|title=2017-18 SAT Performance Statewide Report|work=mass.edu|date=September 20, 2018|access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref>\n|colors = Green & Gold {{color box|green}} {{color box|gold}}\n|mascot = Warrior\n|homepage = {{url|https://www.kingphilip.org/HighSchool}}\n}}\n'''King Philip Regional High School''' is a regional high school in [[Massachusetts]] drawing students from three towns: [[Wrentham, Massachusetts|Wrentham]], [[Norfolk, Massachusetts|Norfolk]], and [[Plainville, Massachusetts|Plainville]].  The school is located at 201 Franklin Street in [[Wrentham, Massachusetts|Wrentham]].\n\n== Marching Band ==\nThe King Philip Regional High School Marching Band, known as \"The Pride and the Passion\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wickedlocal.com/article/20091116/News/311169336|title=KP's Pride and Passion: Marching Band Wins National Title|last=McCarron|first=Heather|date=|website=Wicked Local|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> has traveled throughout New England and the United States for state, regional, and national competitions including [[Massachusetts Instrumental and Choral Conductors Association]] (MICCA) marching band festivals<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://kingphilipmusic.weebly.com/marching-band.html|title=Marching Band|last=|first=|date=|website=King Philip Music Association|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>, [[New England Scholastic Band Association]] competitions<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nesba.org/events/11032019/2019-New-England-Marching-Band-Championships/#|title=NESBA: New England Scholastic Band Association|website=www.nesba.org|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>, [[USBands]] national competitions, and [[Bands of America]] Grand National competitions.\n\nAwards and titles won by the King Philip Marching Band include:\n\n* 33 consecutive MICCA Finals Gold Medal awards (1986\u20142019)<ref name=\":0\" />{{better source|reason=self sourced|date=April 2020}}\n* USBands Group 2 Open Class National Champions (1995)<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://yea.org/usbands/scores|title=USBands Scores|last=|first=|date=|website=yea.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n* USBands Group 3 Open Class National Champions (1998, 1999, 2013, 2015, 2016)<ref name=\":1\" />\n* USBands Group 4 Open Class National Champions (2009, 2012)<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Notable alumni and faculty==\n*[[Lofa Tatupu]] (2001), NFL linebacker<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/players/lofatatupu/profile?id=TAT743820|title=Lofa Tatupu|work=NFL.com|accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Jeff Plympton]], Former Red Sox Pitcher<ref>{{cite web|title=Jeff Plympton - The Baseball Cube|url=http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/P/jeff-plympton.shtml|work=The Baseball Cube |accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Jake Layman]], NBA player (Minnesota Timberwolves)\n*[[Joe Johnson (baseball)|Joe Johnson]], Former MLB Pitcher.<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Johnson Stats|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/j/johnsjo05.shtml|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Jeremy Udden]], musician.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesunchronicle.com/news/kp-grad-jeremy-udden-promotes-hometown-in-plainville-project/article_2adfb967-a2c4-5848-9264-fe9a6602be41.html|title=KP grad Jeremy Udden promotes hometown in 'Plainville' project|work=[[The Sun Chronicle]]|accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Liam Kyle Sullivan]], YouTuber{{citation needed|reason=linked article does not confirm attendance|date=January 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.kingphilip.org/HighSchool}}\n* {{Official|https://www.kingphilip.org/|district website}}\n\n{{Massachusetts Public High Schools}}\n\n{{coord|42|04|22.61|N|71|19|56.45|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Public high schools in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Schools in Norfolk County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Hockomock League]]\n", "name_user": "Rover4844", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moved commas in front of footnotes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/King_Philip_Regional_High_School"}
{"title_page": "Carly Mensch", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Carly Mensch\n| occupation         = Playwright, television writer and producer\n| years_active       = 2007-present\n| television         = [[GLOW (TV series)|GLOW]]\n}}\n\n'''Carly Mensch''' is an American playwright, television writer, and producer. She created an [[Off-Broadway]] play called ''Len, Asleep in Vinyl'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2008/legit/reviews/len-asleep-in-vinyl-1200521957/|title=Len, Asleep in Vinyl|last=Thielman|first=Sam|last2=Thielman|first2=Sam|date=2008-06-03|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/06/theater/reviews/06asle.html|title=Len, Asleep in Vinyl - Review - Theater|last=Gates|first=Anita|date=2008-06-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-08-10|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> which was later adapted into a film, ''[[Len and Company]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/festivals/len-and-company-review-1201525927/|title=Edinburgh Film Review: \u2018Len and Company\u2019|last=Lodge|first=Guy|last2=Lodge|first2=Guy|date=2015-06-27|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> She also created a play ''Oblivion'', which played at the [[Westport Country Playhouse|Westport County Playhouse]], as well as a play called ''All Hail Hurricane Gordo''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/01/nyregion/a-review-of-oblivion-at-westport-country-playhouse.html|title=Accepting a God, and Rejecting Her Parents|last=Gates|first=Anita|date=2013-08-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-08-10|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/newyork/upstaged-blog/a-playwright-speaks-we-interview-carly-mensch|title=A playwright speaks! We interview Carly Mensch {{!}} Theater, Blogs, Upstaged blog {{!}} reviews, guides, things to do, film|website=Time Out New York|language=en|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> She has written and produced for ''[[Weeds (TV series)|Weeds]]'', ''[[Nurse Jackie]]'', and ''[[Orange Is the New Black|Orange is the New Black]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/glow-carly-mensch-liz-flahive-season-2-interview-1202415540/|title=\u2018GLOW\u2019 Showrunners Carly Mensch & Liz Flahive On Comfortable Leotards, Season 2 & \u201cEerie\u201d \u201980s Political Parallels|last=Blyth|first=Antonia|last2=Blyth|first2=Antonia|date=2018-06-22|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> She co-created (with [[Liz Flahive]]) the Netflix series ''[[GLOW (TV series)|GLOW]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/awards/glow-writers-office-kid-friendly-liz-flahive-carly-mensch-interview-1202897052/|title=\u2018GLOW\u2019 Bosses on the Importance of a Kid-Friendly Workspace|last=Turchiano|first=Danielle|last2=Turchiano|first2=Danielle|date=2018-08-09|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> which she currently writes and executive produces. For her work on ''GLOW'', she was nominated for an [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series]] in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/bios/carly-mensch|title=Carly Mensch|website=Television Academy|language=en|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref>\n\nMensch graduated from [[Dartmouth College]] in 2005 and is married to fellow Dartmouth alumnus [[Latif Nasser]], the director of research for [[Radiolab]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dartmouthalumnimagazine.com/latif-nasser-other-latif-podcast|website=Dartmouth Alumni Magazine|title=What\u2019s In a Name?}}\n</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|id=4063230|name=Carly Mensch}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mensch, Carly}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:American television producers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| n